PortList.Description: Ports for accessing a machine using SSH

PortList.Description: Monitor the ports for Remote Applications and all ports except common application ports

IntegrityRule.Name: Microsoft Windows - Attributes of log file modified (ATT&CK T1070, T1222.001)
IntegrityRule.Description:
This rule alerts when there is a change in any file attributes for a given log file on Windows platform. For additional information, see the Details tab.
Note: The rule provides configuration options to add files for monitoring and to select the file attributes to monitor.

LogInspectionRule.Name: Microsoft LDAP Query Execution
LogInspectionRule.Description: To detect Microsoft LDAP query execution in Windows.

LogInspectionRule.Name: Web Server - Apache
LogInspectionRule.Description:
Inspect Apache Web Server for Events
Platform: All supported platforms

LogInspectionRule.Name: Microsoft Windows User Logon Events
LogInspectionRule.Description:
Inspect the event logs of Microsoft Windows operating systems for users successful logon events based on username and logon type id.
Platform: Microsoft Windows
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the username & logon type id, which needs to be monitored. Administrators are advised to configure this rule to make it work.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Rename Activity Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the number of SMB file rename operations during the defined number of seconds. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: The rule also has configuration option to exclude the IPs of the client machines doing rename operations.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Rename Activity Over Network Share - Client
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SMB rename operations over the network.The rule will detect the number of SMB file rename operations during the defined number of seconds. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation on SMB shares for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: The rule also has configuration option to exclude the IPs of the SMB Shares where renames operation can be performed by client machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reflected File Download Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Reflected File Download (RFD) is a web attack vector that enables attackers to gain complete control over a user system. In an RFD attack, the user follows a malicious link to a trusted domain resulting in a file download from that domain.
Note: Configuration option is provided to add the executable file extensions to block the RFD attack for the file extensions. Administrators are suggested to add executable file extensions to block the RFD attack according to their Web Application file extension support. The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm their domain are being used to carry out RFD attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Unvalidated Redirect And Forward Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects Unvalidated redirect and forward in HTTP traffic via request parameters, query string and headers. Unvalidated redirects and forwards are possible when a web application accepts untrusted input that could cause the web application to redirect the request to a URL contained within untrusted input. By modifying unvalidated URL input to a malicious site, an attacker may successfully launch multiple social engineering attacks.
Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted domain/IP in the configuration page. The rule will allow all redirects and forwards unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Access Event Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if Windows Events (Security, Application and System) are accessed by remote machine using 'Psloglist.exe' command line tool through SMBv2 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Access Event Through SMBv1 Protocol Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if Windows Events (Security, Application and System) are accessed by remote machine using 'Psloglist.exe' command line tool through SMBv1 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Client Restrict Executable File Downloads
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks EXE file downloads. Administrator can configure this filter and allow certain EXE file downloads.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A PHP File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of PHP files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: HTTP Protocol Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: Required by all other HTTP DPI rules. This DPI rule decodes the HTTP protocol, restricts URI and query lengths, and validates URI encoding.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious China Chopper Webshell Communication (ATT&CK T1505.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description: China Chopper Webshell is a malware designed to remotely access Windows or Linux Web servers. The malware has a Web shell command-and-control (CnC) client binary and a text-based Web shell payload (server component). Post infection, the malware enables remote attackers to execute arbitrary code on affected systems. This is a heuristic based rule which detects the HTTP communication of China chopper Webshell.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Server Restrict Executable File Uploads (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter blocks EXE file uploads. Administrator can configure this filter and allow certain EXE file uploads.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Attempt To Brute Force Windows Login Credentials (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter identifies a brute force attempt to determine the Windows password by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.
Configuration Note: Customers are advised to use the configuration options to tune the rule as per their environment.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified File Upload Over FTP (ATT&CK T1048.003)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over any network protocol such as HTTP, FTP, SSH other than that of the existing command and control channel. Adversaries may use FTP to exfiltrate the data. This rule monitors the file upload activity over FTP.

PayloadFilter2.Name: HTTP Web Client Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a smart filter that decodes the Web Client traffic and is used by other web client filters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many SSL Alert Messages In SSLv3 Over RDP (ATT&CK T1021.001, T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SSL alert messages from a server within a period of time. Such large number of alert messages could be an indication of block-wise chosen-boundary attack, which could allow an attacker to obtain plain-text bytes using SSLv3 protocol.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events. Multiple alert messages in SSLv3 protocol can occur legitimately due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download Of Executable File Over HTTP (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment. Files may be copied through FTP, HTTP, SSH etc. This rule monitors Linux and Windows executable files being download over HTTP.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMBLoris Denial Of Service Vulnerability
PayloadFilter2.Description:
SMBLoris is a remote and uncredentialed denial of service attack against Microsoft Windows SMB and Unix/Linux Samba servers using memory exhaustion technique. This DPI rule detects an attempt to exploit servers using SMBLoris.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Request Smuggling Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
HTTP Request Smuggling consists of sending a specially formatted HTTP request that will be parsed in a different way by the proxy system and by the final system, so the attacker could smuggle a request to one system without the other being aware of it. This may lead to bypassing Web Application Firewall protection/Web Proxy and improper cache at Web Cache Servers. Please refer the Details section for more information.
Note: This DPI rule should be preferably applied at in-line proxies. Configuration options are provided to block different attack vectors of HTTP Request Smuggling.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMB DLL Injection Exploit Detected (ATT&CK T1055.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is based on heuristics and will detect dll injection attack is being performed using SMB share. This rule could generate many alerts on some network environment hence each trigger needs further investigation to ensure attack.
Note: This rule only detects traffic and does not block.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Radmin Server Remote Control Session Setup (ATT&CK T1219)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Radmin provides an interface to perform several tasks remotely, including remote shutdown, file server functionality, etc. While Famtech's Radmin is a legitimate remote administration application, it is also sometimes associated with malware.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Telegram Bot API Usage (Used by Telecrypt) (ATT&CK T1102.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This filter detects an attempt to use the Telegram API. Telegram is an instant messaging application. The service provides an interface to create custom communication bots.
NOTE: Telegram Bot service has been known to be used by malware like Telecrypt for communication.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Slow HTTP Denial Of Service Attack (ATT&CK T1498.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may attempt to cause a denial of service (DoS) by directly sending a high-volume of network traffic to a target

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious User Agent In Outgoing HTTP Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the suspicious user-agent header in outgoing HTTP request used for connecting to command and control server.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure additional user agents and the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 1 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious User Agent In HTTP Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the suspicious user-agent header of an HTTP request used for scanning and attacking web server or web application.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure additional user agents, remove existing user agents and the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 4 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Operating System Discovery Over SMB Via Nmap Scripting Engine
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect remote operating system discovery over SMB. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate a lot of triggers, therefore triggers should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious TLS Request (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule identifies the malicious TLS request which can be used to compromise a web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious TLS Request - 1 (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule identifies the malicious TLS traffic t which can be used to compromise the web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified SambaShell C&C Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule is intended to block known malicious C&C traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of Linux Executable File (ATT&CK T1608.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detect the upload of a Linux executable file on a web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potential Malicious Client Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potential Malicious Server Traffic (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Account Discovery Over LDAP (ATT&CK T1087.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect remote system discovery over LDAP request for SASL GSS-API SearchRequest. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode For Client
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. This filter will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks in web client traffic

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Command Injection Attack - 1
PayloadFilter2.Description: Command injection is an attack technique that allows an attacker to inject and execute commands in the vulnerable application. An attacker can exploit command injection vulnerability with a command sequence appended to the appropriate format or escape string to execute arbitrary commands. Successful exploitation results in a system compromise, disclosure or modification of data. This is a heuristic based rule to block command injection attacks. In some network environment further investigation will be required to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Permission Groups Discovery Over LDAP (ATT&CK 1069.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect remote system discovery over LDAP request for SASL GSS-API SearchRequest. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Shellcode Over Network Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. This rule will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode Encoders For Client
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. To evade detection or due to protocol constraints, shellcode is often encoded using various shellcode encoders. This filter will identify shellcode encoders that are typically used by automated exploitation tools such as Metasploit.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Image Files Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects malicious BMP and GIF files. Such files can exploit a weakness in image parsing libraries to execute attack on victim's browser.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Microsoft .Net Executable File Upload (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a generic rule to prevent any upload of Microsoft .Net executable over HTTP. Attackers may use malicious Microsoft .NET executable files to cause remote code execution.
Note: This DPI rule should be applied ONLY in server environments where upload of Microsoft .Net executable over HTTP is not allowed.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Upload Of Archive File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to block the upload of certain archive files. The uploaded file could contain malicious code in the form of an exploit, virus, Trojan or malware, which could be used to gain control of the Web server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A JSP File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of JSP files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 3 (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 4 (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Office File With Embedded Executable File
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is intended to block any Microsoft Office file having OLE compound document with embedded executable file. The detection is for identifying such Microsoft Office files when downloaded over web. Attackers may use crafted Microsoft Office files having embedded executable file to run arbitrary code remotely.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Too Many Suspicious TLS/SSL Client Hello Messages (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect too many TLS/SSL Client Hello messages containing a Session Ticket extension with a non-zero Extension Length. With a large number of invalid session tickets, a remote attacker can cause a denial of service.
Note: Configuration options are provided to update the frequency of Client Hello messages.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Web Application Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule blocks brute force attempt to web application by inspecting the number of error responses in a given time period. The IP address is blocked for 20 minutes after the brute force attempt is detected.
Note: Configuration option should be used to enter custom error response.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TLS/SSL RC4 Cipher Suite Is Being Supported (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
The RC4 algorithm, as used in the TLS protocol and SSL protocol, has many single-byte biases, which makes it easier for remote attackers to conduct plaintext-recovery attacks via statistical analysis of ciphertext in a large number of sessions that use the same plaintext.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the RC4 algorithm being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Weak Cipher Support From TLS/SSL Server (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: TLS/SSL server supporting cipher suites based on weak algorithms may enable an attacker to launch man-in-the-middle attacks and monitor or tamper with sensitive data. In general, these ciphers are considered weak. This is a heuristic based rule, which logs SSL traffic with weak Cipher.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Slow HTTP Denial Of Service Attack (ATT&CK T1498.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Slow HTTP Denial-of-Service attacks are caused by exhausting concurrent connection pool and holding connections in open state by sending partial HTTP requests. Tools like Slowhttptest, Slowloris, etc. are used to simulate such DoS attacks. This DPI rule is intended to detect such slow and partial HTTP requests.
Note: By nature of the attack type, this rule may not be able to stop DoS attacks. User configuration options are provided for further customization of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Fraudulent Digital Certificate
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule heuristically prevents the exchange of Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificate whose trust has been revoked.
Ref: Microsoft Security Advisory (2798897).

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict OpenSSL TLS/DTLS Heartbeat Message (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
OpenSSL contains a flaw in its implementation of the TLS/DTLS (Transport layer security protocols) heartbeat functionality which allows an attacker to retrieve sensitive information. This DPI rule is intended to prevent TLS/DTLS heartbeat message coming from a SSL Server.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Compression Algorithm In SSL/TLS Message (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of compression algorithm in SSL/TLS traffic. The TLS protocol can encrypt compressed data without properly obfuscating the length of the unencrypted data, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plaintext HTTP headers by observing length differences during a series of guesses in which a string in an HTTP request potentially matches an unknown string in an HTTP header, aka a "CRIME" attack.
Note: Compression algorithm in SSL/TLS protocol is also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 1 (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TLS/SSL DES Cipher Suite Is Being Supported (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
A cipher block collision vulnerability has been reported in the OpenSSL 3 Data Encryption Standard (3DES) and Data Encryption Standard (DES) ciphers. The vulnerability is due to use of small block size (64-bit) in 3DES. A remote attacker can exploit this vulnerability by monitoring the traffic over long session. Successful exploitation may result in the plaintext recovery of the monitored encrypted traffic.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies the DES algorithm being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified OpenSSL DTLS Anonymous ECDH Cipher Suite (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects the usage of anonymous ECDH ciphersuite in DTLS traffic. OpenSSL DTLS clients enabling anonymous ECDH ciphersuites are subject to a denial of service attack. A malicious server can crash the client with a null pointer dereference (read) by specifying an anonymous ECDH ciphersuite and sending carefully crafted handshake messages.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many Compressed HTTP Responses (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Data compression algorithms can be used by web servers to compress the HTTP responses. BREACH security tool exploits a property of compression algorithms to steal sensitive data. This is a heuristic based rule to identify too many compressed HTTP responses within a period of time.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the count, time period and event frequency of this rule. To monitor SSL Data Stream, agent (DSA) needs to be configured via "SSL Configuration Wizard" and has to acquire the Server SSL certificate where DPI rule is assigned.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified CBC Based Cipher Suite In SSLv3 Request (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 traffic. The CBC Based cipher suites use symmetric encryption algorithm in vulnerable SSL/TLS protocols to encrypt data with chained initialization vectors, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plain-text HTTP headers via a block-wise chosen-boundary attack on an HTTPS session.
Configuration Note: CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 protocol are also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. A configuration option is provided to set the event frequency and to create an approved list of IP addresses that are allowed to communicate using CBC based cipher suite over SSLv3. The filter detects traffic in the default configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSLv3 Response (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SSL version 3.0 Response.
Configuration Note: A configuration option is provided to set the event frequency and to create an approved list of IP addresses that are allowed to communicate over SSLv3. The filter detects traffic in the default configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Download Of DLL File Over WebDAV (ATT&CK T1574.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is based on heuristics and will detect/prevent DLL file being requested to WebDAV server.
Note: This rule should be applied when DLL files are not expected to be downloaded from the WebDAV shares.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated PDF Document (ATT&CK T1027, T1204.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is intended to block suspicious PDF documents which are obfuscated using lexical conventions.
Note: This rule is always recommended when any version of PDF reader is installed on the computer.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Port Mapper Decoder Passive FTP Server
PayloadFilter2.Description: FTP servers can run in Active and Passive modes. In passive mode, the FTP server opens a dynamic port, sends the FTP client the server's IP address to connect to and the port on which it is listening over the control stream and waits for a connection from the FTP client. This filter decodes the FTP port mapper traffic to find out the dynamic port number over FTP control connection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious RTF File With Obfuscated PowerShell Execution (ATT&CK T1027, T1204.002, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule intended to block attempts to load suspicious Microsoft Word RTF files containing PowerShell code, over HTTP traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of EXPORT Cipher Suite In SSLv2 Connection (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Export Cipher suites, as used in the SSLv2 protocol, are very weak and it is easy for remote attackers to conduct plain text-recovery attacks.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies if any Export cipher suites are being used in SSLv2 connection.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Internet Explorer VBScript ShellExecute Command
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the use of VBscript with ShellExceute command in html files, which may allow remote attacker to gain unauthorized access and execute arbitrary code.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks. Customers are advised to configure this rule with allowed IP addresses, from which the VBScript ShellExecute command is allowed to run in Microsoft Internet Explorer.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode In Network Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload to exploit a software vulnerability. The filter will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Revoked Certificate Authority In SSL Traffic (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule prevents the use of revoked/unauthorized Root/Intermediate CAs based on the list of configured CA/Issuers.
Note: Configuration options are provided to configure CA (Certificate Authority).

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected FTP Server Traffic.
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to detect FTP server traffic. Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Using Weak Parameters Client (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is intended to identify Diffie-Hellman Ephemeral Cipher suites using parameters with 512 bits length. The SSL/TLS session keys created with weak parameters could allow an attacker to recover the plain text on the encrypted channel.
This rule will detect if the SSL/TLS client is using DHE weak parameters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of TLS/SSL EXPORT Cipher Suite In Request (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Export Cipher suites, as used in the TLS protocol and SSL protocol, are very weak and it is easy for remote attackers to conduct plaintext-recovery attacks.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies if any Export cipher suite being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified OpenSSL SRP Cipher Suite In Server Hello Message (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects the usage of SRP cipher suite in server hello message. OpenSSL clients enabling SRP ciphersuites are subject to a denial of service attack. A malicious server can crash the client with a null pointer dereference (read) by specifying an SRP ciphersuite even though it was not properly negotiated with the client.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Compression Algorithm In SSL/TLS (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of compression algorithm in SSL/TLS traffic. The TLS protocol can encrypt compressed data without properly obfuscating the length of the unencrypted data, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plaintext HTTP headers by observing length differences during a series of guesses in which a string in an HTTP request potentially matches an unknown string in an HTTP header, aka a "CRIME" attack.
Note: Compression algorithm in SSL/TLS protocol is also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious OpenSSL TLS/DTLS Heartbeat Request (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: The TLS and DTLS implementations in OpenSSL do not properly handle Heartbeat Extension packets, which allow remote attackers to obtain sensitive information from process memory via crafted packets. This is a heuristic based rule to identify such suspicious Heartbeat requests.

PayloadFilter2.Name: FTP Server Restrict Executable File Uploads (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule blocks EXE file uploads. Administrator can configure this rule and allow certain EXE file uploads.
NOTE: This DPI rule only checks the data transfer in PASV mode.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. The filter will identify common shellcode exploits and some zero day attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Malicious Image File
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule is intended to block known malicious image files which are used in attacks in the wild.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote System Discovery Over SMB (ATT&CK T1018)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect remote system discovery over SMB. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: POP3 Mail Server Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule blocks brute force attempt to POP3 mail server by inspecting the number of invalid login attempts in a given time period. The IP address is blocked for 20 minutes after the brute force attempt is detected.
Note: Configuration option can be used to enter error responses of the mail server to be monitored.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of A Class File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of Class files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified SSL/TLS Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange Using Weak Parameters Server (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is intended to identify Diffie-Hellman Ephemeral Cipher suites using parameters with 512 bits length. The SSL/TLS session keys created with weak parameters could allow an attacker to recover the plain text on the encrypted channel.
This rule will detect if the SSL/TLS server is using DHE weak parameters.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Obfuscated JavaScript - 2 (ATT&CK T1203, T1001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects suspicious obfuscated JavaScript used by attackers to bypass security and gain unauthorized access to the system. Legitimate web sites could also obfuscate code to reduce security exposure or for intellectual property protection.
Note: The triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm attacks.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified HTTP Redhat Webshell C&C Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: FTP Server Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Domain-Level Account Discovery Over SMB (ATT&CK T1087.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect domain account discovery over SMB. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Restrict Attempt To Enumerate Windows User Accounts (ATT&CK T1087)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter identifies an attempt to enumerate user account information on a Windows host. There are valid cases where an administrator may want to enumerate accounts on a remote system but any alert from this filter should be investigated. Note: This rule should not be assigned to domain controllers.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Telnet Server Possible Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter detects a brute force attempt to gain the Telnet Server Password by inspecting the number of failed logins in a time period. An attacker may use automated tools to iterate through all combinations or use a dictionary attack to guess passwords.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many SSL Alert Messages In SSLv3 Traffic (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many SSL alert messages from a server within a period of time. Such large number of alert messages could be an indication of block-wise chosen-boundary attack, which could allow an attacker to obtain plain-text HTTP headers on an HTTPS session using SSLv3 protocol.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events. Multiple alert messages in SSLv3.0 protocol can occur legitimately due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SSLv3 Request (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SSL version 3.0 Request.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this filter.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified CBC Based Cipher Suite In SSLv3 Response (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects the usage of CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 traffic. The CBC Based cipher suites use symmetric encryption algorithm in vulnerable SSL protocol to encrypt data with chained initialization vectors, which allows man-in-the-middle attackers to obtain plain-text HTTP headers via a block-wise chosen-boundary attack on an HTTPS session.
Note: CBC Based cipher suites in SSLv3.0 protocol are also used for legitimate purpose due to server limitations. Hence, every trigger of this rule should be investigated further to confirm an attack. Configuration options are provided to customize the alert frequency of the events.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Upload Of An Archive File (ATT&CK T1190)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to identify the upload of Archive files to a Web Server. These files could be potentially harmful for running applications and could be used for further attacks.
Note: Configuration options have been provided to select the file extensions. Without configuration rule will not be able to identify the upload of any kind of archive files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of TLS/SSL EXPORT Cipher Suite In Response (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Export Cipher suites, as used in the TLS protocol and SSL protocol, are very weak and it is easy for remote attackers to conduct plaintext-recovery attacks.
Note: This is a heuristic based rule which identifies if any Export cipher suite being used in SSL/TLS traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Fraudulent Digital Certificate - 1
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically prevents the exchange of Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificate whose trust has been revoked.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified DLL Side Loading Attempt Over Network Share (ATT&CK T1574.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
DLL side-loading vulnerability specifically occur when Windows Side-by-Side (WinSxS) manifests are not explicit enough about characteristics of the DLL to be loaded. Attackers may take advantage of a legitimate program that is vulnerable to side-loading to load a malicious DLL. Successful exploitation of this vulnerability could lead to remote code execution. This rule detects attempts to load DLL files which are not signed by Microsoft or Adobe Corporation over network shares.
Note: Triggers of this rule need to be analyzed further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) Connection Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to identify Remote Desktop connection request using Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP). In some network environment, many RDP connection requests, could lead to Denial of Service (DOS) condition. After the frequency of RDP connection requests matched as per the configuration this rule will prevent any further RDP connection for the configured period of time.
Note: Configuration options are provided to customize the number of requests and the time interval. Administrators are also suggested to add trusted IP addresses in the configuration page.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Suspicious DLL Side Loading Attempt Over WebDAV (ATT&CK T1574.002)

DLL side-loading vulnerability specifically occur when Windows Side-by-Side (WinSxS) manifests are not explicit enough about characteristics of the DLL to be loaded. PayloadFilter2.Name: Multiple SSH Connections Detected (ATT&CK T1499.002, T1110)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) Brute Force Attempt (ATT&CK T1110)

PayloadFilter2.Description: Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and help other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Finger Service Traffic (ATT&CK T1021)

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reflected File Download Attack in URI Query Parameter
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Reflected File Download (RFD) is a web attack vector that enables attackers to gain complete control over a user system. In an RFD attack, the user follows a malicious link to a trusted domain resulting in a file download from that domain.
Note: Configuration option is provided to add the executable file extensions to block the RFD attack for the file extensions. Administrators are suggested to add executable file extensions to block the RFD attack according to their Web Application file extension support. PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many Incoming HTTP Requests
PayloadFilter2.Description:

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TTF File/OTF File Download

Note: This filter detects and blocks the use of TeamViewer

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Subnet Discovery Over LDAP (ATT&CK T1016)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may look for details about the network configuration and settings of systems they access or through information discovery of remote systems. This rule detects the subnet discovery request over LDAP.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Download Of Restricted File Formats (ATT&CK T1105)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment. Files may be copied through FTP, HTTP, SSH etc. This rule detects files being download over HTTP.
Note: With default configuration rule monitors ".tmp, .dat, .sh, .ps1" files from being download over HTTP. Also configuration option is provided to add more file extensions to monitor.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Executable File Download On Network Share Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is based on heuristics and will detect executable file being accessed over SMB share. Hence this rule should only be applied when executable files are not used over the SMB Share.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Add Job Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if a Job is added remotely through SMBv2 Protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote Service Creation Over DCE/RPC Protocol (Invoke-SMBexec Tool)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule detects remote service creation over DCE/RPC protocol. Attackers may install a new service that can be configured to execute at startup by using utilities to interact with services or by directly modifying the registry. These services can be leverage to escalate privileges from administrator to SYSTEM.
Note: This rule when applied might generate number of events depending upon the environment. Also, triggers of this rule have to be investigated further to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft BAT And CMD Files Over WebDAV
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to detect .bat and .cmd files being accessed over WebDAV. A remote code execution vulnerability exists in the way that Microsoft Windows processes .bat and .cmd files that are run from an external network. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could take complete control of an affected system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Image With Embedded PHP Code
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is a heuristic based rule to detect malicious php code embedded within gif, jpg and png image files. An attacker may use maliciously crafted image file to do remote code execution and take control of the victim's host machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Microsoft Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and helps other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 3 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Too Many HTTP Requests With Specific HTTP Method
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect too many HTTP ( GET, POST, HEAD etc.) requests to a web server within a period of time. Such large number of HTTP requests to a web server could be used to launch DDoS attack.
Note: Configuration options are provided to update the alert frequency for HTTP requests and HTTP methods.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Reverse Shell Communication Over HTTPS - 2 (ATT&CK T1071.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule heuristically detects the initial communication between the compromised machine and C&C server.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SMTP Decoding
PayloadFilter2.Description: The filter decodes the SMTP Protocol and will be used by other SMTP filters. It should be enabled on all the SMTP filters. The filter will have to be active on application type listening on port 25.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Remote System Discovery Over LDAP (ATT&CK T1018)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule is to detect remote system discovery over LDAP request for SASL GSS-API SearchRequest. This technique is used by adversaries in lateral movements to collect the information about compromised network.
Note: In some network environment, this rule could generate lots of trigger, therefore trigger should be investigated further to confirm attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Microsoft DLL File Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote code execution vulnerability exists in the way that the Microsoft Windows handles the loading of DLL files. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could take complete control of an affected system. This rule is based on heuristics and will only detect DLL file being accessed over SMB share. Hence this rule should be applied when DLL files are not used over the network.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Disallow Packed Executable Download Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects the transfer of executables ,over HTTP, which are packed with known versions of packers commonly used for malicious executables.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode In Microsoft Office Files
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability which attempts to execute code without the affected user's consent. This is a heuristic based rule to identify common shellcode exploits in office files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Windows Group Policy Files Downloaded From Untrusted Sources
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule identify domain-joined computers downloading Group Policy files from untrusted sources.
This rule is intended to protect against attacks where the client machine is being redirected to execute a malicious Group Policy file hosted in malicious sever. By default, this rule will not block any machine or Domain Controller server. Configuration options are provided to add the trusted Domain Controller IPs.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Microsoft Windows Shortcut File Over Network Share (ATT&CK T1080)
PayloadFilter2.Description: A remote code execution vulnerability exists in the Microsoft Windows Shell. Windows incorrectly parses shortcuts in such a way that malicious code may be executed when the user clicks the displayed icon of a specially crafted shortcut.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Unsecured Credentials - Cloud Instance Metadata API (ATT&CK T1552.005)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects attempts to access the Cloud Instance Metadata API and collect credentials and other sensitive data. It currently protects workloads on the following Cloud Service Providers: Amazon Web Services, Google Cloud Platform and Microsoft Azure.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Usage Of PAExec Command Line Tool (ATT&CK T1569.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
PAExec is a command line tool that execute processes on remote systems and redirect console application output to the local system so that these applications appear to be running locally. This rule identifies the use of PAExec tool through SMB share. PAExec is very powerful tool and used by malware and exploits for lateral movement in the network.
Configuration Note: Administrators are suggested to add trusted IP addresses in the configuration page. The rule will block all PAExec attempts unless configured.

PayloadFilter2.Name: WinRM Service Detected & Powershell RCE Over HTTP (ATT&CK T1021.006, T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Windows Remote Management (WinRM) is the name of both a Windows service and a protocol that allows a user to interact with a remote system (e.g., run an executable, modify the Registry, modify services). This filter detects its generic usage as well as through PowerShell.
Note: In some network environments, this rule can generate many triggers and will need further investigation to confirm an attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Image File With Embedded PHP Code
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule is a heuristic based rule to detect malicious php code embedded within gif, jpg and png image files. An attacker may use maliciously crafted image file to do remote code execution and take control of the victim's host machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Diginotar Certificate
PayloadFilter2.Description: This filter heuristically blocks exchange of Secure Socket Layer (SSL) certificate issued by Diginotar.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Service Execution Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects, if execution of service is being performed remotely through SMBv2 protocol using 'SC' command line option.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Downloading Of PowerShell Scripts Through SMB Share (ATT&CK T1059.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description: PowerShell may also be used to download and run PowerShell scripts from the Internet, which can be executed from disk or in memory without touching disk. Adversaries may use PowerShell to execute malicious PowerShell scripts that may cause Damage of the system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified NTLMv1 Authentication Attempt Over SMB
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule detects NT LAN Manager (NTLM) Authentication Protocol which is used in Microsoft Windows workgroups for authentication between clients and servers.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this rule. By default, this rule blocks all NTLMv1 traffic. Administrators are advised to configure this rule with IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious JavaScript Encoded Shellcode
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload to exploit a software vulnerability. This filter detects suspicious web browser exploits and some zero day attacks that use JavaScript to encode shellcode.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Server Suspicious SMB Session
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects the usage of suspicious SMB command used to create covert channels in SMB. This kind of attack is used by attack payloads like doublepulsar.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Client Suspicious SMB Session
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule detects the usage of suspicious SMB command used to create covert channels in SMB. This kind of attack is used by attack payloads like doublepulsar.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Microsoft Windows OLE Remote Code Execution Vulnerability Over SMB
PayloadFilter2.Description: A vulnerability exists in Windows OLE that could allow remote code execution if a user opens a file that contains a specially crafted OLE object over SMB. An attacker who successfully exploited this vulnerability could gain the same user rights as the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified TCP Meterpreter Payload
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Meterpreter is an advanced and extensible Backdoor that is stealthy and highly resilient to detection. Additionally, it is used in post-exploitation attacks as a means to establish a foothold on an infected network. Moreover, it is generated by Metasploit, the penetration testing framework. Note that Meterpreter is also known as Beacon with other adversary simulations and red team operations frameworks such as CobaltStrike and Armitage.
Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Delete Job Through SMBv1 Protocol Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if a 'delete' Job command being performed remotely through SMBv1 Protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Malware Activity
PayloadFilter2.Description: This DPI rule is intended to detect the "Operation DeputyDog" campaign leveraging the Internet Explorer zero-day CVE-2013-3893.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Network Share Discovery (ATT&CK T1135)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may look for folders and drives shared on remote systems as a means of identifying sources of information to gather as a precursor for Collection and to identify potential systems of interest for Lateral Movement.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified File Deletion From SMB Share (ATT&CK T1070.004)
PayloadFilter2.Description: Adversaries may delete files left behind by the actions of their intrusion activity. Malware, tools, or other non-native files dropped or created on a system by an adversary may leave traces to indicate to what was done within a network and how. Removal of these files can occur during an intrusion, or as part of a post-intrusion process to minimize the adversary's footprint.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified User Creation Attempt In GitStack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects an attempt to create a user in GitStack software.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to set the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Create Activity Over Network Share (ATT&CK T1486, T1080)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB create operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file create operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file create, write and delete operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Windows Client Port Mapper Decoder
PayloadFilter2.Description: Remote Procedure Call (RPC) is an interprocess communication (IPC) mechanism that enables data exchange and invocation of functionality residing in a different process. A client will call the endpoint mapper (EPM) at the server to ask for a "well known" service. The server will answer the client at which port this service is available. This rule decodes the port shared by the Server using DCE/RPC Endpoint Mapper (EPM) Protocol, and help other rules for monitoring traffic on the dynamically opened port.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Many SSH Client Key Exchange Requests (ATT&CK T1499.002, T1110)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SSH client key exchange requests from the same source IP. Many client key exchange requests in short span of time are highly suspicious. This DPI rule could be helpful in identifying SSH bruteforce attack.
Note: Configuration options are provided to change the frequency to alert on.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Windows DCERPC AUTH LEVEL CONNECT Password Validate Request
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule, which detects if the AUTH LEVEL CONNECT is used as a DCERPC level authentication protection for Password Validate request. AUTH LEVEL CONNECT is not secure, an attacker having MITM situation could tamper the traffic and discover other domain passwords.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Download Of XML File Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule prevents the download of large XML file over HTTP. Attackers may use crafted XML files to cause remote code execution. It may corrupt memory in such a way that an attacker could execute arbitrary code in the context of the logged-on user.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Bash ShellShock Attack
PayloadFilter2.Description:
Bash is prone to a remote code execution vulnerability when it incorrectly processes trailing strings after certain malformed function definitions in the values of environment variables, which allows remote attackers to write to files or possibly have unknown other impact via a crafted request. This is a heuristic based rule to detect such attacks.
Note: In some network environment this rule could generate many alerts, hence every trigger should be investigated further to confirm the attack.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected SMB Request
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic rule intended to detect SMB version 1,2 and 3 requests. By default rule only monitors all SMB versions.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the event frequency of this rule and the SMB versions to monitor.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Rename Activity Over Network Share
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file rename operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation from that source for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions and IPs of the client machines doing rename operations.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Possible Ransomware File Extension Rename Activity Over Network Share - Client
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristic based rule to detect SMB rename operations over the network. The rule will detect the file extensions used during the file rename operations. After the malicious source is detected the rule will prevent any further SMB file rename and write operation to the network share for the defined period of time.
Configuration Note: This rule has configuration parameters to monitor and to exclude the file extensions and the IPs of the SMB Shares where renames operation can be performed by client machine.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified WebNMS Framework Server Sensitive File Access (ATT&CK T1552.001)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects an attempt to access a sensitive installation file in WebNMS Framework Server. While not inherently malicious, known vulnerabilities exist in which an unauthorised entity could access sensitive installation information in WebNMS Framework Server. An attacker could leverage this to obtain passwords for all user accounts.
Configuration Note: Configuration options are provided to set the IP(s) of trusted host(s) to pass traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Suspicious Usage Of Shellcode Encoders
PayloadFilter2.Description: Shellcode is a piece of machine code used as the payload in the exploitation of a software vulnerability. To evade detection or due to protocol constraints, shellcode is often encoded using various shellcode encoders. This filter will identify shellcode encoders that are typically used by automated exploitation tools such as Metasploit and Canvas.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Anonymous/Default FTP Login Attempt Detected
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule to detect the FTP login using default/Anonymous login. Anonymous FTP accounts can allow unauthorized access to a system.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote File Copy Over FTP (ATT&CK T1544, T1071.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This rule detects download of a file over FTP.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Remote Schedule Task 'Create' Through SMBv2 Protocol Detected (ATT&CK T1053.005)
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristic based rule which detects if 'Create' Scheduled Task command is performed by the remote machine using 'SchTasks' command line options through SMBv2 protocol.

PayloadFilter2.Name: SSL/TLS Client (ATT&CK T1573.002)
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This DPI rule detects SSL/TLS client traffic based on heuristics.
Note: Configuration options are provided to set the protocols disallowed, ports monitored and event frequency of the rule.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Microsoft Office File With Embedded TIFF File
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This rule is intended to block any Microsoft Office file embedded with TIFF over web. Attackers may use crafted Microsoft Office files having embedded TIFF file to run arbitrary code remotely.
Note: TIFF files can be embedded in Microsoft Office files in multiple ways. This rule detects TIFF files embedded in Microsoft Office in certain known ways. And the rule does not detect Microsoft Office Open XML format (docx, pptx, etc.) files.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Harmful Client Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified Potentially Harmful Server Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description: This is a heuristics based filter to prevent potentially harmful traffic.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Detected Wget Client Traffic
PayloadFilter2.Description:
This is a heuristics based filter to detect HTTP Client traffic by using Wget user agent. For mission critical servers, limited HTTP client traffic means those servers will have less exposure to web related attacks. It also prevents potential backdoor software from contacting external malicious sites.
This filter will be triggered once per minute for a given host. The frequency of event settings can be modified on the Configuration tab should your environment require different configuration.

PayloadFilter2.Name: Identified BumbleBee Webshell Traffic Over HTTP
PayloadFilter2.Description: This alert is triggered when traffic matching a known Command and Control pattern is observed. Events from this filter are typically indicative of network activity from a breached host.

PayloadFilter2Metadata.Value: Authentication failed Access denied logon failure

ConnectionType.Name: SAP NetWeaver Java Application Server
ConnectionType.Description:
These ports are used for communication with the NetWeaver AS Java as part of SAP NetWeaver Application Server. Ports are : TCP\50000 - 50001.
Reference : https://help.sap.com/viewer/ports Search Java on this page and it shows.

ConnectionType.Name: Web Server Common
ConnectionType.Description: Smart and vulnerability facing filters common to all web servers.

ConnectionType.Name: Zoho ManageEngine
ConnectionType.Description:
As of now, this apptype is meant for following Zoho applications : 1. Zoho ManageEngine Applications Manager 2. Zoho ManageEngine OpManage 3. Zoho ManageEngine Desktop Central 4. Zoho ManageEngine AssetExplorer
We can add more applications using HTTP protocol in this apptype in future. If any particular app is having more rules then we can create separate apptype for that application in future.

ConnectionType.Name: Web Server SharePoint
ConnectionType.Description: Using SharePoint people can set up Web sites to share information with others, manage documents from start to finish, and publish reports to help everyone make better decisions.

ConnectionType.Name: Windows Remote Management Client
ConnectionType.Description: Identify the usage of WinRM on client machine to detect the originating machine in case of using WinRM for lateral movement.

ConnectionType.Name: DCERPC Services
ConnectionType.Description: Remote procedure call (RPC) is a protocol that is used by the Windows and Linux (Samba) operating system. RPC provides an inter-process communication mechanism that allows a program that is running on one computer to seamlessly access services on another computer. The protocol itself is derived from the Open Software Foundation (OSF) RPC protocol.
